value.name: Description
value.value: The pickups capture the vibrations of the strings, in order to turn them into sound. Each one has a very unique tone.

value.name: Description
value.value: Here you can select the pickup(s) you want to use.

value.name: Description
value.value: With the whammy bar, you can change the pitch of the notes you play. This video shows its most popular, as well as disturbing application in rock history.

value.name: Caption
value.value: You've guessed it: The song medley you just heard, was made only using the four basic chords you can see above. The purple dots tell you to put a finger on that specific string on that specific fret. The white dots are strings you play without holding them down, and an X means, to not play the string at all. Now, there are mainly two things you can do with your chords:

value.name: Description
value.value: This is the note "C", so the C-chord starts here. The note we play on the lowest string is (almost) always the root note of the chord.

value.name: Caption
value.value: You've made it! You've totally mastered your axe! While you're practicing, a Finnish metal band is driving past your window. They are just blown away by your talent. Looking for a new lead guitarist, they instantly hire you, and thanks to your amazing talent, you become famous in no time.

value.name: Caption
value.value: Theres a new girl in your school. Lindsey. Needless to say, her beauty is beyond compare!

value.name: Caption
value.value: One day, Lindsey takes Chad to one of your concerts. When granted backstage access, she instantly dumps Chad, and you two live happily ever after.

value.name: Caption
value.value: Now THAT was amazing! Now you're probably thinking, that you'll never be as good as him... Well, yeah, most probably not! But have a look at his left hand. Notice, how it basically rests at the same place most of the time?

value.name: Caption
value.value: From now on, you practice you pentatonic every day.

value.name: Caption
value.value: A few weeks later, you are perfectly fluid in playing Wonderwall on your guitar.

value.name: Caption
value.value: In order to win over Lindsey, you collect all your savings to buy yourself a shiny new guitar! Unfortunately, you have no clue how to play it...

value.name: Caption
value.value: Strumming belongs to the absolute guitar basics. You hold your chords, and use your right hand to go down-down-up-down-down-... or whatever fits the song. It takes some practice, to really make the chords "sing". You can use your fingers or a pick, that's a matter of personal taste.

value.name: Caption
value.value: You and Lindsey live happily ever after.

value.name: Caption
value.value: Not much to see here right now. Use one of the back buttons above to get back to the previous page.

value.name: Caption
value.value: Travis Picking is probably the guitar technique with the highest cost-benefit ratio. All you have to do is hold your chord, and instead of just strumming the strings, you pluck them individually in a nice pattern. This is the part, that will require some practice, but the result will soon sound highly professional!

value.name: Caption
value.value: You really start to enjoy playing the guitar. The years go by, and you become quite a professional.

value.name: Caption
value.value: At your prom, you are able to play a small solo performance live on stage.

value.name: Text
value.value: That's it. High school is over, and you've spent most of your time at home playing guitar.

value.name: Text
value.value: The neck is where most of the magic happens. This one has a rosewood fretboard. The vertical sections are called "frets". After the 12th one, the notes start to repeat themselves.

value.name: Description
value.value: They make the guitar sound sharper or warmer.

value.name: Caption
value.value: "That was, uhm, quite nice, I guess!?", Lindsey stutters, as she texts Chad.

value.name: Caption
value.value: Let's ignore the theory behind this for now. The dots you see above, denote a set of notes you can play that, combined, will always sound pleasant. You'll be surprised to see, how many famous solos just consist of some messing-around with this shape. Training your fingers to move fluently across it, is half the battle.

value.name: Caption
value.value: To your disadvantage, she is completely obsessed with Chad, the handsome guy who plays in a band. Stupid Chad!

value.name: Caption
value.value: Once you understood the system behind that, you can basically just google the correct fret for each song.

value.name: Text
value.value: Okay, the notes in this shape might always sound good together, but what if they don't match the song? That's the cool thing about the guitar: You can play this pattern at different places, to match different songs. Want to solo to "Eye of the Tiger"? Put it on the 8th fret. "Billie Jean"? 2nd fret...
